-- U.S.-based stock funds attract $10 billion over week-Lipper 
-- By Luciana Lopez
-- Thu Jun 12, 2014 05:06PM EDT
-- None



NEW YORK, June 12 (Reuters) - Investors in U.S.-based funds committed $10 billion to stock funds in the week ended June 11 after adding $3.7 billion to the funds the prior week, data from Thomson Reuters' Lipper service showed on Thursday.

Stock mutual funds attracted $2.4 billion in new cash, while stock exchange-traded funds drew $7.6 billion. Stock mutual funds are commonly purchased by retail investors, while stock ETFs are thought to represent the institutional investor. Taxable bond funds attracted $1.2 billion in new cash, marking their fourteenth straight week of inflows. Money market funds posted net outflows of $1.6 billion, their fifth straight week of outflows.